+# Compute-optimal visible-spectrum results review
+
+The run in `compute_optimal_visible` uses `a=1.5`, `b=1.4`, and
+`theta in {0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1}`.  The results support the theorem in
+`notes/18_compute_optimal_visible_scaling.md`.
+
+The critical visibility threshold is
+
+```text
+theta_c = 2(1 - b/a) = 2(1 - 1.4/1.5) ≈ 0.1333.
+```
+
+Therefore only `theta=0` is in the hard-source/time-limited phase.  All rows with
+`theta >= 0.25` are in the variance-limited phase, where the compute-risk exponent
+saturates at
+
+```text
+(b - 1) / (b + 1) = 0.4 / 2.4 = 1/6 ≈ 0.1667.
+```
+
+This explains why the observed risk exponent is essentially constant across
+`theta=0.25,0.5,0.75,1`, while the optimal effective horizon and learning-rate
+exponents keep changing.
+
+Recommended next compute runs:
+
+```bash
+python experiments/compute_optimal_phase_grid.py
+```
+
+The most important subrun is `hard_full_range`, which uses `a=3.0,b=1.4`.  In
+that setting the whole interval `theta in [0,1]` remains time-limited, so the
+compute-risk exponent should improve monotonically with visible spectral
+information.
