+++ b/notes/19_visibility_phase_transition.md
+# 19. Visibility phase transition and compute-exponent saturation
+
+The compute-optimal experiment `compute_optimal_visible` confirms the theorem in
+`18_compute_optimal_visible_scaling.md`, but it also reveals an important
+interpretation point: increasing the visible spectral exponent \(\theta\) need not
+keep improving the **asymptotic compute exponent** forever.  Once the problem
+enters the variance-limited/easy-source phase, further spectral flattening mainly
+improves constants and the optimal learning-rate schedule, while the compute-risk
+exponent saturates.
+
+This note makes that phase transition explicit.
+
+## Setup
+
+Let the covariance eigenvalues obey
+
+\[
+    \lambda_i\asymp i^{-a},
+    \qquad a>1,
+\]
+
+and suppose the target source condition is
+
+\[
+    s_i=\lambda_i\langle v_i,w^\star\rangle^2\asymp i^{-b},
+    \qquad b>1.
+\]
+
+Let the visible spectral profile exponent be \(\theta\in[0,1]\).  The effective
+preconditioned covariance exponent is
+
+\[
+    \alpha(\theta)=a(1-\theta/2).
+\]
+
+The simplified sharp risk proxy is
+
+\[
+    R(M,N,K)-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    M^{1-b}+K^{1-b}+\frac{K}{N},
+\]
+
+with compute budget
+
+\[
+    C\asymp MN
+\]
+
+and algorithmic constraint
+
+\[
+    K\le N^{1/\alpha(\theta)}.
+\]
+
+## Theorem 1: compute exponent as a function of visibility
+
+Let
+
+\[
+    m(\theta)=\max\{\alpha(\theta),b\}.
+\]
+
+Then the compute-optimal allocation is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    M_\star(C)\asymp C^{1/(m(\theta)+1)},
+    \qquad
+    N_\star(C)\asymp C^{m(\theta)/(m(\theta)+1)},
+}
+\]
+
+and
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    R_\star(C)-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    C^{-\beta(\theta)},
+    \qquad
+    \beta(\theta)=\frac{b-1}{m(\theta)+1}.
+}
+\]
+
+The learned-mode count satisfies
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    K_\star(C)\asymp C^{1/(m(\theta)+1)}.
+}
+\]
+
+The optimal effective horizon and learning-rate scale are
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    n_\star(C)\asymp C^{\alpha(\theta)/(m(\theta)+1)},
+    \qquad
+    \gamma_\star(C)\asymp C^{(\alpha(\theta)-m(\theta))/(m(\theta)+1)}.
+}
+\]
+
+### Proof
+
+For fixed \(N\), the unconstrained minimizer of
+
+\[
+    K^{1-b}+K/N
+\]
+
+satisfies
+
+\[
+    K\asymp N^{1/b}.
+\]
+
+The algorithm can learn at most
+
+\[
+    K\asymp N^{1/\alpha(\theta)}.
+\]
+
+Therefore
+
+\[
+    K_\star(N)\asymp N^{1/\max\{\alpha(\theta),b\}}=N^{1/m(\theta)}.
+\]
+
+The remaining risk is
+
+\[
+    M^{1-b}+N^{-(b-1)/m(\theta)}.
+\]
+
+With \(C=MN\), balancing these two terms gives
+
+\[
+    M_\star^{1-b}\asymp (C/M_\star)^{-(b-1)/m(\theta)}.
+\]
+
+Solving yields
+
+\[
+    M_\star\asymp C^{1/(m(\theta)+1)},
+    \qquad
+    N_\star\asymp C^{m(\theta)/(m(\theta)+1)}.
+\]
+
+Substitution gives the claimed risk exponent.  The formulas for \(K_\star\),
+\(n_\star=K_\star^{\alpha(\theta)}\), and \(\gamma_\star=n_\star/N_\star\)
+follow immediately.
+
+## Theorem 2: visibility threshold and saturation
+
+Define the critical visibility
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \theta_c=2\left(1-\frac{b}{a}\right).
+}
+\]
+
+If \(0<\theta_c<1\), then
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\beta(\theta)=
+\begin{cases}
+\dfrac{b-1}{a(1-\theta/2)+1}, & 0\le \theta\le \theta_c,\\[10pt]
+\dfrac{b-1}{b+1}, & \theta\ge \theta_c.
+\end{cases}
+}
+\]
+
+Thus the compute exponent improves with \(\theta\) only until
+
+\[
+    \alpha(\theta)=b.
+\]
+
+After that point the problem is variance-limited and the exponent saturates.
+
+If \(\theta_c\le0\), the problem is already variance-limited at \(\theta=0\), so
+visibility improves constants but not the asymptotic compute exponent.  If
+\(\theta_c\ge1\), the whole interval \(\theta\in[0,1]\) remains time-limited, so
+visibility improves the compute exponent throughout the interval.
+
+### Proof
+
+The phase boundary is
+
+\[
+    \alpha(\theta)=b.
+\]
+
+Since
+
+\[
+    \alpha(\theta)=a(1-\theta/2),
+\]
+
+solving gives
+
+\[
+    \theta_c=2(1-b/a).
+\]
+
+For \(\theta\le\theta_c\), we have \(\alpha(\theta)\ge b\), hence
+\(m(\theta)=\alpha(\theta)\).  For \(\theta\ge\theta_c\), we have
+\(m(\theta)=b\).  Substituting into Theorem 1 proves the piecewise expression.
+
+## Interpretation of the current compute experiment
+
+The run in `experiments/results/compute_optimal_visible` uses
+
+\[
+    a=1.5,
+    \qquad
+    b=1.4.
+\]
+
+Therefore
+
+\[
+    \theta_c=2(1-1.4/1.5)\approx 0.1333.
+\]
+
+Only the \(\theta=0\) row is in the hard-source/time-limited phase.  All tested
+values \(\theta\ge0.25\) are already in the variance-limited phase, so the risk
+exponent should saturate at
+
+\[
+    \frac{b-1}{b+1}=\frac{0.4}{2.4}=\frac16\approx0.1667.
+\]
+
+This is exactly what the compute-optimal results show: the risk exponent becomes
+nearly constant for \(\theta\ge0.25\), while the optimal effective learning-rate
+exponent keeps changing with \(\theta\).
+
+## Recommended additional compute experiments
+
+To display a monotone compute-exponent improvement across the full range of
+\(\theta\), choose a larger covariance exponent, e.g.
+
+\[
+    a=3,
+    \qquad
+    b=1.4.
+\]
+
+Then
+
+\[
+    \alpha(1)=a/2=1.5>b,
+\]
+
+so the entire interval \(\theta\in[0,1]\) remains in the hard-source phase.  The
+prediction becomes
+
+\[
+    \beta(\theta)=\frac{b-1}{a(1-\theta/2)+1},
+\]
+
+which increases from \(0.1\) at \(\theta=0\) to \(0.16\) at \(\theta=1\).
+
+A second useful run adds AdamW-style weight decay.  With fixed \(\delta>0\), the
+learned-mode count should saturate once
+
+\[
+    n_\star(C)\gtrsim \delta^{-1}.
+\]
+
